post_text:
It has come to our attention that an individual recently altered a social media post by the WCHS Student Council for the purpose of making a political statement and to potentially cause a disruption at tonight’s football game. The original post was merely to encourage students to show school spirit by wearing red, white, and blue to school and to the football game in honor and in memory of those who lost their lives on September 11, 2001.
We recognize everyone’s first amendment right to freedom of expression, but the law is very clear that statements and/or actions that disrupt school and school-sponsored activities are not permissible and will not be tolerated.
We would like to remind everyone that the best sources for reliable information are WCBOE media outlets such as system/school websites, Facebook pages, and our Kinvo messaging system. Please do not rely upon the comments or posts of individuals to get accurate information about school-related activities.
Dr. Jay Brinson, Superintendent Wayne County School System

post_text: Wayne County High School Class of 2020 graduate Darren Malone (right), recently graduated from Basic Combat Training at Fort Jackson, SC, and was selected as the “Soldier Leader of the Cycle” out of a company of 200 trainees. WCHS JROTC instructor First Sergeant Brandon Short states, “Exuding excellence, leadership ability and distinguishing yourself above your peers is the road to success in the military, and this young man is off to a great start. I applaud all faculty and staff in the Wayne County School System who contributed to his education and growth. HOOAH!”

post_text: As you all are aware, Governor Kemp has mandated to shelter in place through April. Due to the uncertainty of the future, WCHS has to make necessary decisions concerning upcoming events. The safety and health of all students, their families, and staff members is of the utmost concern. With that being said, we will postpone Prom 2020 and Senior Supper indefinitely. It is our goal to keep as many of WCHS’ time-honored traditions intact and will work diligently to do so. The COVID-19 situation will continued to be monitored and we will provide updates on future events as we make decisions. Thank you and stay safe!

Clear your schedule for Saturday, March 7th. Big Brothers and Big Sisters of Wayne County will have a Scholarship Benefit Concert at Unity Church of God's Gym. No need to dress up. Come as you are.

They are offering space for churches to set up to sell items, food, etc. They only ask that you make a donation. The amount is up to you.

Admission is FREE. We are accepting donations from individuals to reach our goal of $1000.

If your church is interested in setting up a booth or if you know an individual who is a vendor contact Sheron Daniel at 912-202-2086 for more information.

Please view the comment below for added schedule information.

post_text: The United States Presidential Scholars Program was established in 1964, by Executive Order of the President, to recognize and honor some of our Nation's most distinguished graduating high school seniors. If selected at the national level, students receive an expenses paid trip to Washington D.C. to meet with government officials, educators and other accomplished people. Wayne County High School recently named two students as nominees for this program. Pictured are from left to right, Michelle Poinsett, WCHS nominee in the career and technical education fields, Principal Dr. Brett McDaniel, and Ki Riddle, nominee in the area of academic achievement.

post_text: Wayne County High School recently named Ki Riddle as its United States Senate Youth Program nominee. This program was established in 1962 by the United States Senate to provide a unique educational experience for outstanding high school students interested in pursuing careers in public service. Two finalists from each state are chosen to participate in a week long program in Washington D.C. each spring. Pictured are from left to right, Principal Dr. Brett McDaniel and the USSYP nominee for WCHS, Ki Riddle.

post_text: Wayne County High School recently named its 2020 Hugh O’Brian Ambassador and alternate. The Hugh O’Brian Youth Leadership program recognizes outstanding 10th grade students for their leadership ability. These students will be eligible to participate in a seminar during the summer where they will participate in hands on leadership activities and meet leaders in their state. Pictured from left to right are the 2020 Hugh O’Brian Ambassador Luke Hendrix, Principal Dr. Brett McDaniel, and 2020 Alternate Jack-Ryan Peterson.

post_text:
Ten students were recently chosen as Wayne County High School’s nominees for the Governor’s Honors Program. The Georgia Governor’s Honors Program (GHP) is a residential summer program at Berry College for gifted and talented high school students who will be rising juniors and seniors during the program. If selected at the state level, students will participate in intensive study in their areas during four weeks during the summer. Pictured are from left to right:
Bottom row – Imari Franklin, Kush Patel, Levi Cooksey, and Savannah Beasley.
Middle row: Anna-Marie Lege’, Principal Dr. Brett McDaniel, and Lance Vickery.
Top Row: Luke Hendrix, Acie Moody, Avery Blalock, and Mollie Martin.

post_text: Students at MPMS have a new addition to the cafeteria, a hydroelectric system growing basil, lettuce, and arugula to serve more nutritious items. Local farmer Sonya Jones from Lanes Bridge Lettuce helped manager in training Nicki Roberson implement this unique method of growing to teach students more about hydroponics. The hydroponic method of growing allows plants to grow without soil by using a nutrient rich water solution.

Homecoming T-Shirts are available for purchase through Jacket Zone, the school store. Below is a proof of this year’s shirt that goes along with our school theme and homecoming theme for the year. The school theme is “WCHS Hits in the Making”, and our Homecoming Theme is “Platinum Homecoming”.

These shirts help support the Senior class in their activities for the year. Please support them by purchasing a shirt, showing your spirit by wearing it, and sharing the link with those not in the school system. This is open to anyone!

Because we are on a tight timeline, orders must be placed by Thursday, September 26th at lunch to have them in time to distribute Thursday, October 3. We will continue to sell them afterwards as spirit shirts, but we will not guarantee them for Homecoming if orders are placed after this Thursday. Thank you again!

Shirt Details:
Bella Canvas Brand
Short sleeve ($16) or long sleeve ($21)
Youth and adult sizes
Link to Purchase: https://wchs-jacket-zone.square.site/

post_text:
Wayne County Graduation Rate At An All-time High!

The Wayne County High School graduation rate for SY18-19 was 93.8% --- an all-time high for the county! That’s up from 90% in SY17-18. The chart below shows how Wayne County did in comparison to the other systems in our geographic area. This county has so much to be proud of. High School Principal, Dr. McDaniel, his admin team and faculty and staff are to be congratulated. Although the graduation rate is directly reflected in the work taking place at the high school, we also recognize that it all begins in the early elementary years and continues on into upper elementary and middle school so we would like to extend a very special word of thanks to ALL of the teachers, administrators, support staff at each of our eight schools and to the parents of all of our students.. YOU ROCK!!! Thanks to everyone for all you do every single day to help the children of our community!

Important Announcement:

- Beginning with this Friday’s Wayne County High School football game, all children in 6th grade and under must be accompanied by an adult and must be seated in the bleachers unless they are moving to and from the restroom or concession stand.

- Children will no longer be allowed to be dropped off and left unsupervised.

- All spectators - students and adults - will be required to be seated in either the home or visitors’ bleachers.

- Spectators may not congregate on the track, at the concession stands, or behind the bleachers.

- If asked to find a seat by a school official or law enforcement officer, please politely comply.

- Spectators who fail to comply after being asked to be seated will be directed to leave the stadium.

- Parents of children refusing to comply will be notified to pick them up immediately.

We appreciate your cooperation as we implement these changes are for the safety and enjoyment of all spectators.

post_text: Twenty-two teachers took their first steps into the Wayne County School System on Wednesday, July 31, as they participated in New Teacher Orientation at the WCSS Tech Center. Teachers were introduced to the superintendent, directors, central office support staff members, principals, assistant principals, and instructional coaches before observing the exceptional practices of two of Wayne County’s model classroom teachers. Tina Moseley, Human Resources Director, and Amy Denty, Director of Curriculum & Instruction, facilitated the morning orientation sessions. Later in the day the new teachers had an opportunity to meet their mentor-teacher who will work closely with them throughout the year.

Teachers were introduced to the superintendent, directors, central office support staff members, principals, assistant principals, and instructional coaches before observing the exceptional practices of two of Wayne County’s model classroom teachers. Tina Moseley, Human Resources Director, and Amy Denty, Director of Curriculum & Instruction, facilitated the morning orientation sessions. Later in the day the new teachers had an opportunity to meet their mentor-teacher who will work closely with them throughout the year.

post_text: Mentor-Teachers from all schools came together at the Tech Center on July 30, 2019 to learn about how they can be of assistance to the new teachers who will be joining the Wayne County School System this year. Mentors will encourage the professional development and growth of brand new teachers as well as veteran teachers who are coming to our system for the first time. Mentors will guide the new teachers in developing their planning, instruction, and content knowledge. Tina Moseley, Human Resources Director, conducted the training for the 23 mentors in attendance.

post_text: Twenty educators from the Wayne County School System participated in the Spring WorkSource Wayne Day on April 10, 2019. Middle and high school teachers, administrators and support staff toured the facilities EAM and Healthy Pet in order to get an idea of what manufacturing employers are seeking in job candidates so they better prepare students for potential careers. Following the tours, the group went to Coastal Pines Technical College to take part in a Lunch-and-Learn with Chad Swanson and Carley McDonald of CPTC to learn more about the dual enrollment program in which high school students can also earn college credit and earn certification in various technical fields.

post_text:
PROTECT YOUR STUDENT PRESENTATION

Is it really a federal offense?

Through social media and technology, our students are exposed to so many opportunities that it makes keeping a close eye very difficult. As a joint effort between AWMS, the Jesup Police Department, and the Wayne County Sheriff's Department, we aim to help you identify ways to protect our students from becoming involved in illegal issues such as bullying, cyberbullying, drugs, alcohol, and tobacco. We invite all parents, community members, and students to attend this event at AWMS on 1/24/2019 at 6pm. All AWMS students represented will receive a homework pass to be used in any academic class.
